Spring boot generated über jar for a simple `CommandLineRunner` app currently does not support being executed from a Windows UNC path such as `java -jar \\myhost\myshare\my-sb-app.jar`.

Boot first raises an `Unable to determine code source archive` `IllegalStateException` thrown by [Launcher](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/fa88c481a5ee5c431ca2c11e297a0330ed71da74/spring-boot-tools/spring-boot-loader/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/loader/Launcher.java#L151) because `path` variable don't get the leading "//" sequence.

This can be easily fixed by :

``` diff
    URI location = (codeSource == null ? null : codeSource.getLocation().toURI());
-   String path = (location == null ? null : location.getPath());
+   String path = (location == null ? null : location.getSchemeSpecificPart());
    if (path == null) {
```

Second is in [ExecutableArchiveLauncher#createClassLoader](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/blob/fa88c481a5ee5c431ca2c11e297a0330ed71da74/spring-boot-tools/spring-boot-loader/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/loader/ExecutableArchiveLauncher.java#L80) where some wrong `file://myhost/myshare/my-sb-app.jar` URL is added to the `copy` variable while it should have been `file:////myhost/myshare/my-sb-app.jar` and subsequently ripped off by `#addDefaultClassloaderUrl`.

This time I don't know how to fix it for good (hence I'm not posting a PR), my dirty workaround is :

``` java
        if (loader instanceof URLClassLoader) {

final URL badURL = MyApplication.class.getProtectionDomain().getCodeSource().getLocation();
final URL goodURL = getArchive().getUrl();

            for (URL url : ((URLClassLoader) loader).getURLs()) {

if (url.equals(badURL)) {
    url = goodURL;
}

                if (addDefaultClassloaderUrl(urls, url)) {
                    copy.add(url);
                }
            }
        }
```

`loader` is `sun.misc.Launcher$AppClassLoader` running from JRE 7.

I have a spring-boot application from which I explicitly exclude a dependency from the packaged jar due to licensing issues (and the size of the dependency). We deploy this required dependency in production in a`/lib` directory and instruct spring-boot to look for it there using the PropertiesLauncher and `-Dloader.path`

This works as expected. However, if operations forget to deploy this dependency and try to start the application it exits without any hint as to what might be wrong.

I debugged the application and discovered that a `java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError` is thrown when refresh is called on an ApplicationContext that states the name of the missing class. This information would be enough for us to realise that the issue is a missing dependency but is not logged anywhere.

Although I realise that you should not normally catch subclasses of `java.lang.Error` it would be really helpful if we sent the error message to the logger by appending something like this to the try / catch in `SpringApplication.run(String...)`

```
} catch (Error e) {
    log.error("Application startup failed", e);
    throw e;
}
```
